### Phase 4: Feature Engineering — Player Level
**Sessions:** 9-11 | **Time:** ~6-8 hours

> **Playing XI approach:** Player features are NOT computed from historical lineups.
> Instead, the user inputs the actual playing XI **after the toss is announced** (when
> squads are confirmed). The pre-computed player stats lookup table is ready — at
> prediction time you pass 11 player names and the system fetches their stats and
> aggregates to team-level features on the fly. Historical training still uses the
> players who appeared in each past match (derived from deliveries.csv) for that match.

**What Claude Code builds:**
```
STEP 1: Compute player career stats from deliveries.csv
  For each batter (from ball-by-ball data):
  • total_runs, balls_faced, dismissals
  • batting_average = runs / dismissals
  • strike_rate = (runs / balls) × 100

  For each bowler:
  • runs_conceded, balls_bowled, wickets
  • economy_rate = (runs / balls) × 6
  • bowling_strike_rate = balls / wickets

STEP 2: Rolling player stats (stats as of each match date)
  Same computation but only using matches before current date.
  This captures CURRENT FORM, not just career averages.
  → Export as player_career_stats.json (keyed by player name, for fast lookup at prediction time)

STEP 3: Aggregate to team level per match
  For TRAINING: derive XI from deliveries.csv (players who batted/bowled = the XI)
  For PREDICTION: user inputs 11 player names post-toss → system looks up their stats
  Given the 11 players in a team's lineup for a specific match:

  BATTING (features 25-28):
  25. team_a_avg_batting_sr (mean SR of top 7 batters in XI)
  26. team_a_avg_batting_avg (mean batting avg of top 7)
  27. team_b_avg_batting_sr
  28. team_b_avg_batting_avg

  BOWLING (features 29-32):
  29. team_a_avg_bowling_econ (mean economy of top 5 bowlers)
  30. team_a_avg_bowling_sr (mean bowling SR of top 5)
  31. team_b_avg_bowling_econ
  32. team_b_avg_bowling_sr

  EXPERIENCE (features 33-34):
  33. team_a_total_ipl_caps (sum of matches played by XI)
  34. team_b_total_ipl_caps

  STAR POWER (features 35-38):
  35. team_a_best_batting_avg (max in XI)
  36. team_b_best_batting_avg
  37. team_a_best_bowling_econ (min/best in XI)
  38. team_b_best_bowling_econ

STEP 4: Player Matchup Features (what real broadcast systems use)
  For the two XIs, compute historical batter-vs-bowler records:
  Each ball in deliveries.csv has a batter AND bowler — mine this directly.

  For each (batter, bowler) pair that has faced at least 6 balls:
  → runs_scored, balls_faced, dismissals
  → batter_vs_bowler_sr = (runs / balls) × 100
  → batter_vs_bowler_dismissal_rate = dismissals / balls

  Then aggregate across the two XIs:
  MATCHUP (features 39-44):
  39. team_a_favorable_matchups   ← count of A batters with SR > 140 vs assigned B bowlers
  40. team_b_favorable_matchups
  41. team_a_avg_matchup_sr       ← mean SR of A's top-order vs B's likely bowling attack
  42. team_b_avg_matchup_sr
  43. team_a_key_wicket_threat    ← highest dismissal rate bowler in B's XI vs A's top-3
  44. team_b_key_wicket_threat

  NOTE: This is the closest publicly achievable version of what franchises
  do internally. Real systems use every ball ever bowled per pairing;
  so do we — deliveries.csv has 200K+ balls with batter and bowler columns.

Output: full_features.csv — 44 feature columns + target per match
```

**What you learn:**
```
• Complex groupby with multiple columns and aggregations
• How to extract playing XI from deliveries.csv
  (players who batted or bowled in a match = the XI)
• merge() with different join types (left, inner)
• Handling edge cases: players with <5 matches (unreliable stats)
• Why we aggregate to team level (model can't handle 22 variable-length player inputs)
• How to mine batter-vs-bowler matchup data from ball-by-ball records
• Why matchup features add signal beyond team-level averages
```

