### Phase 8: Model B — Live Win Probability (Data Prep)
**Sessions:** 18-19 | **Time:** ~6-8 hours

**What Claude Code builds:**
```
RECONSTRUCT MATCH STATE AFTER EVERY BALL from deliveries.csv:
(This is how real broadcast systems work — not over-by-over, ball-by-ball)

For each match, for each ball in the 2nd innings:
  → Compute: score, wickets, ball number, CRR, RRR, runs remaining,
    balls remaining, wickets in hand
  → Label: did the chasing team eventually win? (1/0)

This creates ~120 rows per match × 500+ chaseable matches = 60,000-80,000 rows
(6× more training data than over-by-over, captures single-ball swings)

  CLASS IMBALANCE NOTE:
  In blowout chases (e.g., team needs 220, collapses early), 80 of 120
  ball-snapshots for that match are labeled "chasing team lost". This can
  bias the model to predict "loss" too often at early balls.
  Fix: use class_weight='balanced' in Logistic Regression, and
  scale_pos_weight in XGBoost. Check class distribution before training.

BASE FEATURES (12):
1.  current_score
2.  wickets_fallen
3.  balls_bowled           ← ball-level (not overs_completed)
4.  target
5.  runs_remaining
6.  balls_remaining
7.  wickets_in_hand
8.  current_run_rate
9.  required_run_rate
10. run_rate_ratio (CRR / RRR)
11. venue_chase_win_rate
12. batting_team_chase_win_rate

IN-MATCH MOMENTUM FEATURES (6 new — this is the "real system" difference):
13. powerplay_score_vs_venue_avg
    → (score at end of over 6) minus (venue's historical avg powerplay score)
    → positive = ahead of average pace → chaser is in control
14. last_6_balls_runs        ← runs in the last 6 deliveries (last "over" equivalent)
15. last_6_balls_wickets     ← wickets in last 6 deliveries (pressure metric)
16. dot_ball_pct_last_12     ← % dot balls in last 12 deliveries (tells you if batter is stuck)
17. current_partnership_balls ← how long the current partnership has lasted
18. wickets_in_last_3_overs  ← momentum shift indicator

TARGET: chasing_team_won (1/0)

Output: live_model_data.csv
```

**What you learn:**
```
• How to reconstruct match state ball-by-ball (not just over-by-over)
• Cumulative sum within groups: df.groupby('match_id').cumsum()
• Rolling window calculations: .rolling(6).sum() for last-6-balls stats
• Why ball-by-ball matters: a wicket on ball 3 of an over is invisible
  until the over ends — over-level models are blind to it for 5 balls
• Why momentum features matter: CRR/RRR alone can't tell if a team is
  collapsing under pressure vs comfortably coasting
• Creating a fundamentally different dataset from the same raw data
```

