### Phase 12: CricAPI Live Data Integration
**Sessions:** 28-29 | **Time:** ~4-6 hours

**What Claude Code builds:**
```
LIVE DATA PIPELINE:
1. Sign up for CricAPI free tier (cricketdata.org)
   RATE LIMIT WARNING: Free tier = 100 calls/day.
   A live match lasts ~4 hours. Polling every 60s = 240 calls just for one match.
   Strategy: poll every 90s during match hours only (skip overnight polls).
   This keeps daily usage under 100 calls for one match per day.
   If you need to test during non-match hours, use saved fixture JSON instead.
   API key MUST be stored in a .env file (CRICAPI_KEY=xxx), never hardcoded.

2. Background task in FastAPI that:
   - Checks every 90 seconds during match window: is there a live IPL match?
   - If yes: fetches current score JSON
   - Parses: score, wickets, overs, target, batting team, bowling team
   - Feeds into Model B's feature engine
   - Updates prediction
   - Pushes to frontend via polling (frontend polls /api/live-feed every 15s)
3. Fallback: if API is down or rate limit hit, switch to manual mode automatically

CRICAPI RESPONSE (example):
  {
    "status": "live",
    "batting_team": "Mumbai Indians",
    "bowling_team": "Chennai Super Kings",
    "score": "98/3",
    "overs": "11.2",
    "target": "185",
    ...
  }

PARSE → MODEL INPUT:
  {
    "current_score": 98,
    "wickets": 3,
    "overs": 11.33,
    "target": 185,
    ...
  }

→ Model B predicts: MI 62.3%, CSK 37.7%
→ Frontend updates probability meter automatically
```

**What you learn:**
```
• External API integration (requests + API keys)
• Background tasks in FastAPI
• Polling architecture (frontend polls backend, backend polls CricAPI)
• Error handling for external APIs (rate limits, downtime)
• Real-time data pipeline design
```

